      <p>The common thread across these careers is the combination of human connection, creative or intellectual depth, and a sense of purpose. INFJs need to believe their work matters. A high salary in a meaningless role will leave an INFJ feeling hollow, while modest compensation in work they find deeply meaningful can sustain them for decades.</p>
      <p>INFJs should be cautious about careers that involve constant high-volume social interaction without depth (such as retail sales), highly competitive environments with little collaboration (such as cutthroat corporate finance), or repetitive, detail-heavy administrative roles that offer no opportunity for vision or creativity. While INFJs can function in these environments, they are unlikely to thrive in them long-term.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Famous INFJs</h2>
      <p>While typing historical and public figures is inherently speculative, several notable individuals are widely considered to exhibit classic INFJ traits. Examining their lives can illuminate how the INFJ's unique combination of vision, empathy, and quiet determination manifests in extraordinary achievement.</p>
      <p><strong>Martin Luther King Jr.</strong> is perhaps the quintessential example of an INFJ in action. His ability to articulate a transcendent vision ("I Have a Dream"), his deep empathy for the suffering of others, his unwavering moral conviction, and his strategic, structured approach to social change all reflect the Ni-Fe-Ti-Se function stack. He combined the INFJ's visionary idealism with a practical determination to create real change, even at great personal cost.</p>
      <p><strong>Nelson Mandela</strong> demonstrated the INFJ's capacity for long-term vision and principled endurance. Spending 27 years in prison without abandoning his vision for a reconciled South Africa reflects the INFJ's ability to hold onto an internal vision (Ni) with extraordinary patience. His emphasis on reconciliation over retribution after his release reflects the Fe drive toward harmony and the well-being of the broader community.</p>
      <p><strong>J.R.R. Tolkien</strong> channeled the INFJ's rich inner world into one of the most elaborate and beloved fictional universes ever created. The depth of Middle-earth, its languages, histories, mythologies, and moral frameworks reflects the Ni-dominant mind's ability to construct vast, internally consistent visions. Tolkien's themes of humble courage, the corrupting nature of power, and the importance of mercy over justice all resonate with INFJ values.</p>
      <p>Other individuals frequently typed as INFJ include Fyodor Dostoevsky, whose novels plumb the depths of human psychology and morality; Mahatma Gandhi, whose nonviolent resistance embodied INFJ idealism and strategic vision; and Plato, whose philosophical frameworks sought to describe ideal forms of truth, beauty, and justice.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>INFJ vs INFP: Key Differences</h2>
      <p>INFJ and INFP are two of the most commonly confused personality types. They share three letters, both are introverted idealists, and both care deeply about authenticity and meaning. However, beneath the surface similarities, they operate in fundamentally different ways due to their entirely different cognitive function stacks.</p>

      <div style="overflow-x:auto;margin:1.5rem 0">
        <table style="width:100%;border-collapse:collapse;background:var(--color-surface);font-size:0.95rem">
          <thead>
            <tr style="border-bottom:2px solid var(--color-border)">
