              <th style="padding:0.75rem;text-align:left">INFJ</th>
              <th style="padding:0.75rem;text-align:left">INFP</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr style="border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-border)">
              <td style="padding:0.75rem">Dominant Function</td>
              <td style="padding:0.75rem">Introverted Intuition (Ni) - converges on a single vision</td>
              <td style="padding:0.75rem">Introverted Feeling (Fi) - guided by internal values</td>
            </tr>
            <tr style="border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-border)">
              <td style="padding:0.75rem">Auxiliary Function</td>
              <td style="padding:0.75rem">Extraverted Feeling (Fe) - absorbs others' emotions</td>
              <td style="padding:0.75rem">Extraverted Intuition (Ne) - explores many possibilities</td>
            </tr>
            <tr style="border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-border)">
              <td style="padding:0.75rem">Decision Making</td>
              <td style="padding:0.75rem">More decisive and structured; prefers closure</td>
              <td style="padding:0.75rem">More flexible and open-ended; dislikes premature decisions</td>
            </tr>
            <tr style="border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-border)">
              <td style="padding:0.75rem">Emotional Style</td>
              <td style="padding:0.75rem">Absorbs others' emotions (emotional sponge)</td>
              <td style="padding:0.75rem">Processes emotions internally; deeply personal value system</td>
            </tr>
            <tr style="border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-border)">
              <td style="padding:0.75rem">Conflict Approach</td>
              <td style="padding:0.75rem">Seeks harmony and resolution for the group</td>
              <td style="padding:0.75rem">Stands firm on personal principles regardless of group opinion</td>
            </tr>
            <tr style="border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-border)">
              <td style="padding:0.75rem">Work Style</td>
              <td style="padding:0.75rem">Organized, plans ahead, likes to complete projects</td>
              <td style="padding:0.75rem">Adaptable, may juggle multiple projects, struggles with deadlines</td>
            </tr>
            <tr style="border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-border)">
              <td style="padding:0.75rem">Focus</td>
              <td style="padding:0.75rem">Outward impact on people and systems</td>
              <td style="padding:0.75rem">Inward authenticity and self-expression</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <p>The most reliable way to distinguish between the two types is to examine the feeling function. INFJs use Extraverted Feeling (Fe), which is oriented toward the emotional atmosphere of the group. They naturally prioritize harmony, consensus, and the emotional well-being of those around them. INFPs use Introverted Feeling (Fi), which is oriented inward. They are guided by a deeply personal set of values and ethics that they apply consistently regardless of social pressure. An INFP is more likely to say "This is what I believe, and I will stand by it even if no one agrees." An INFJ is more likely to say "I sense what the group needs, and I will work to bring people together."</p>
      <p>Another significant difference is in how they generate ideas. INFJs converge (Ni), meaning they take in information from many sources and synthesize it into a single, clear insight or vision. INFPs diverge (Ne), meaning they take a single idea and explore it in multiple directions, generating many possibilities and connections. This is why INFJs tend to be more focused and decisive, while INFPs tend to be more exploratory and open-ended.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>How to Thrive as an INFJ</h2>
      <p>Being an INFJ comes with extraordinary gifts but also genuine challenges. The following strategies can help INFJs leverage their strengths while managing the vulnerabilities that come with their type.</p>
      <p><strong>Protect your energy with firm boundaries.</strong> Your empathy is a gift, but it is also a finite resource. Learn to recognize the difference between compassion and emotional absorption. You do not have to carry everyone else's pain. Practice saying no without guilt and schedule regular alone time as a non-negotiable part of your routine. Boundaries are not selfish; they are essential maintenance for your ability to care for others sustainably.</p>
      <p><strong>Ground yourself in the physical world.</strong> Your inferior Se means you can easily get lost in your head. Deliberately cultivate activities that anchor you in the present moment: exercise, cooking, gardening, hiking, playing music, or any form of physical creative expression. These activities are not distractions from your real work. They are essential counterbalances that keep you connected to your body and to the tangible world.</p>
      <p><strong>Communicate your needs before you reach your limit.</strong> The INFJ door slam usually happens because you suppressed your needs for too long, hoping the other person would notice on their own. They will not. Most people do not have your level of emotional perception. Practice expressing your needs clearly and early, even when it feels uncomfortable. A relationship where you have to hide your true feelings to maintain harmony is not actually harmonious. It is a time bomb.</p>
      <p><strong>Challenge your perfectionism.</strong> Your Ni can see the ideal, and that vision can become a prison. Practice releasing work before it is perfect. Adopt the mantra "done is better than perfect" and remind yourself that imperfect action creates more impact than perfect inaction. Your first draft, first attempt, or first version is almost certainly better than you think it is, because your standards are calibrated to a level of excellence that most people would consider exceptional.</p>
      <p><strong>Find your people.</strong> INFJs thrive with a small circle of deep, authentic connections rather than a large network of acquaintances. Invest in relationships with people who appreciate your depth, respect your introversion, and are willing to go beyond surface-level conversation. These connections are your emotional lifeline, and having even two or three truly understanding relationships can transform the INFJ experience from one of isolation to one of profound belonging.</p>
      <p><strong>Embrace your rarity.</strong> You are different from most people, and that difference is not a defect. It is a feature. The world needs people who can see what others cannot, who feel what others do not notice, and who are driven by meaning rather than convention. Stop trying to be more like everyone else and start leveraging what makes you uniquely powerful. Your sensitivity, your vision, and your depth are not weaknesses to overcome. They are capacities to develop and deploy in service of the causes and people you care about most.</p>
    </section>

