      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>What does INFJ stand for?</summary>
        <p>INFJ stands for Introverted, Intuitive, Feeling, and Judging. These four preferences describe how INFJs gain energy (through solitude), process information (through abstract patterns and future possibilities), make decisions (through values and empathy), and organize their lives (through structure and planning). INFJs are the rarest of the 16 Myers-Briggs types, making up about 1 to 3 percent of the population. <a href="/test/personality-type-test/">Take our Personality Type Test</a> to discover your type.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Why is INFJ the rarest personality type?</summary>
        <p>INFJ is the rarest type because it combines four preferences that are each individually less common in the population, and their specific combination is the least statistically frequent. The dominant function, Introverted Intuition (Ni), is itself rare and appears as a dominant function only in INFJs and INTJs. The pairing of deep internal vision (Ni) with strong external empathy (Fe) creates an unusual cognitive profile that naturally occurs in only a small percentage of people.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What is the difference between INFJ and INFP?</summary>
        <p>Despite sharing three letters, INFJs and INFPs have completely different cognitive function stacks. INFJs lead with Introverted Intuition (Ni) and use Extraverted Feeling (Fe), making them convergent thinkers who absorb others' emotions and seek group harmony. INFPs lead with Introverted Feeling (Fi) and use Extraverted Intuition (Ne), making them values-driven individuals who explore many possibilities and prioritize personal authenticity over consensus. INFJs tend to be more structured and decisive, while INFPs are more flexible and individualistic.</p>
      </details>
    </section>

